pr_review_comment_body:
@bastibe I don't think there is reason for concern here. The `repr()` mentions some CFFI type, but it is really just like any other Python buffer object.

I think it's the right thing to use buffer objects, since those are the lowest level Python data structures and supported by many built-in and third-party libraries.

Many things *might* also work with `bytearray()`, but I see no advantage in wrapping the buffers in `bytearray`s.

Why not do the `if` in the `except` just to wrap the `log.warning` call?

```python
try:
   claims = jwt.decode(token, …, audience=audience)
except jwt.InvalidTokenError as e:
    if audience:
        log.warning('Invalid matched audience')
    else:
        log.warning('Invalid JWT token')
```

I do not know the mechanics exactly, but somehow Celery copies the dependent modules of the script that it runs on the worker node. Say you run execution engine on the worker (`celery_run.delay(self.executor, data_id, script, verbosity)
 `). The engine that runs on the worker node spawns new processes. This would trigger a run of the manager on the worker node. The manager then resolves dependencies and runs the spawned processes. Celery somehow knows it has to copy the `managers/celery.py` to the worker node so it can be imported and executed. However you import the function in a method (like here) to avoid circular dependencies instead of on the top, this somehow messes up Celery. 

@dblenkus should know more about this and if we have a test for this in resolwe. Here is a test for demultiplexing: https://github.com/genialis/resolwe-bio/blob/master/resolwe_bio/tests/processes/test_demultiplex.py.

Our policy templates follow the pattern of forcing scoping the resource to the current account and region for tighter security. Will following this pattern work for your use case? For example, you could change the SecretArn parameter to SecretName. Then do this:

```
"Resource": {
  "Fn::Sub": [
    "arn:${AWS::Partition}:secretsmanager:${AWS::Region}:${AWS::AccountId}:secret:${secretName}",
    {
      "secretName": {
        "Ref": "SecretName"
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

Can you add some alignment and spacing here to make this more readable?
```
port_get_config_defaults(&pin_conf);
pin_conf.direction  = PORT_PIN_DIR_OUTPUT;

port_pin_set_config(AT86RFX_SPI_SCK,  &pin_conf);
port_pin_set_config(AT86RFX_SPI_MOSI, &pin_conf);
port_pin_set_config(AT86RFX_SPI_CS,   &pin_conf);
.....
```
